    <section id="fs-id1169738181556" class="section-summary"><title>Section Summary</title><list id="fs-id1169737822145">
    <item id="import-auto-id1169738111021">Electromagnetic waves are created by oscillating charges (which radiate whenever accelerated) and have the same frequency as the oscillation.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id1169737724680">Since the electric and magnetic fields in most electromagnetic waves are perpendicular to the direction in which the wave moves, it is ordinarily a transverse wave.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id1169738137705">The strengths of the electric and magnetic parts of the wave are related by
    <equation id="eip-967"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mi>B</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext> c</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id1169737755364">which implies that the magnetic field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>B</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is very weak relative to the electric field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>E</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</para>
    </item>
        </list>
